<observation>
        <p>
Showing <m>T:V\to W</m> is <em>not</em> a linear transformation can be done by finding an example
for <em>any one</em> of the following.
<ul>
<li>
    <p>
    Show <m>T(\vec 0)\not=\vec 0</m> (where <m>\vec 0</m> is the additive identity of <m>V</m> and <m>W</m>).
    </p>
</li>
<li>
    <p>
    Find specific values for <m>\vec v,\vec w\in V</m> such that <m>T(\vec v+\vec w)\not=T(\vec v)+T(\vec w)</m>.
    </p>
</li>
<li>
    <p>
    Find specific values for <m>\vec v\in V</m> and <m>c\in \IR</m> such that <m>T(c\vec v)\not=cT(\vec v)</m>.
    </p>
</li>
</ul>
</p>
        <p>
Otherwise, <m>T</m> can be shown to be linear by proving <em>both</em> of the following <em>in general</em>.
<ul>
<li>
    <p>
    For all <m>\vec v,\vec w\in V</m>, <m>T(\vec v+\vec w)=T(\vec v)+T(\vec w)</m>.
    </p>
</li>
<li>
    <p>
    For all <m>\vec v\in V</m> and <m>c\in \IR</m>, <m>T(c\vec v)=cT(\vec v)</m>.
    </p>
</li>
</ul>
</p>
        <p>
Note the similarities between this process and showing that a subset of a vector
space is or is not a subspace (<xref ref="EV3-subspace-check"/>).
        </p>
</observation>


